segments.text: I guess it was 16 years ago.
He wanted me to meet George Mitchell.
So I met George Mitchell, and at that time, he had become very much involved in the issue of sustainable societies and limits to growth.
And so I got involved with the Club of Rome.
and decided he would commit himself to these five biannual conferences, international conferences dealing with the issue.
At that time, he called it Limits to Growth.
And I knew absolutely nothing about that and cared less.
I thought it was futurism and I wasn't going to get involved in that, but President Hoffman persuaded me otherwise.
And I'm delighted he did.
Anyway, as a result of that first interaction,
over the last, ever since then, there's just been a series of activities and projects that I've gotten, I've been involved with George Mitchell.
To finally about, I don't know, maybe six years ago, in the early stages of HARC, he asked me to serve as interim director of HARC, interim president.
And during the next few months, the search began for a president, and Skip Porter was recruited.
And when I was done with that, he asked me to do something else related to his dream of having a campus out here.
He had this gift on the table at the University of Houston for all these years, and then he had to come with it.
And that was followed by
something related to the research for us and finally he and I talked and I said that I think I was ready for the switch.
I just wanted to do something different.
I thought this was a wonderful opportunity to enter the private sector and really earn some big money.
My timing was perfect.
I hadn't been here two weeks when the energy market collapsed
Real estate went down the tubes.
And he was kind enough not to hold me responsible.
University life looked pretty good.
University life looked better than ever.
When was that?
Was that about 83?
And it was interesting.
His major concern was giving up tenure.
He had this thing about tenure was probably a, what?
He's got tremendous, tremendous respect.
I think sometimes it borders on naivety about university life.
I mean, I think he really does.
The idea of somebody leaving the university, particularly with that tenure, and going into this risky, chancy, free market world.
He was genuinely concerned about that.
You know, I told him that was not something that he had to be concerned with, that that was a decision.
that I could make.
What he had to be concerned with was coming up with something that I would find attractive enough.
And he did, and that was not a problem.
So I've been here ever since as vice president for institutional development.
It's a wonderful job.
I mean, it's a reflection of Mitchell.
Who else would hire a PhD in sociology?
Who knows?
Nothing about real estate knows nothing about energy.
It's kind of interesting, because I have a lot of colleagues.
and say, you know, I've been thinking seriously about getting into the private sector.
How do you do that?
And I said, listen, find another Mitchell.
That's all I can tell you.
So I continued to work with him on a variety of activities.
How precisely, you mentioned that Holmes, was it President Holmes?
Hoffman.
Hoffman.
Introduced you to George Mitchell.
What was that initial, what did you do initially?
Initially was to help him design, structure his first biannual conference on, it's called Limits to Growth.
Oh.
And that's when the Club of Rome was involved, and that first one, Dennis Meadows, who at Dartmouth had written several books on limits to growth and sustainable societies.
There was a lot of interest in that topic.
And George came up with some very, very nice prizes, five prizes of $10,000 each, and really put up a lot of money to do this for his conference.
And then after the first conference on Limits to Growth, George realized that after all, he was calling for more and more energy exploration.
He was a land developer.
And he really didn't believe that we had reached the limits to growth.
But he was much more comfortable with the notion of sustainable society.
And he's got a tremendous commitment to protecting the environment, the ecology.
You don't just have to look around here.
The guy is very, very reluctant.
I mean, there's many, many opportunities for him to sell land at a very great profit.
He won't simply because of the needs
or putting buildings, commercial buildings, and giving up frontage and so on.
So I was involved with that.
Then he had this great vision and the need for economic diversification for Houston and Texas.
And he became very much aware that there were a lot of exciting and viable inventions and discoveries coming out of Texas, particularly out of the universities.
But much of it was going elsewhere because there was no venture capital here.
The only thing the banks were interested in was investing in oil.
He once told a story of some guy walks into a bank and says, I have a cure for cancer.
And they say, we can't do anything for you.
And the other guy walks in and says, I have a black box.
He says, what's in there?
He says, a new way of getting oil.
He says, here's a million dollars.
He then formed the Woodlands Venture Capital Company and put up five million dollars.
Hired a guy to really start.
Fifteen's over there.
Oh, fifteen's over there.
It's five and then five and then five.
It's a total of fifteen.
Hired Marty Sutter, who came in to run Woodlands Venture Capital.
And just about the same time,

We started to think of this consortium of Texas universities that could come together at the Woodlands and really work on big-ticket items, complement one another, and create a major basic research center that would have spin-offs for commercialization.
And you got involved in that early on?
Right, right, yeah.
I was asked, I chaired the feasibility committee.
At that time, UT was not involved.
A&M was involved, U of H, and Rice.
And they had very good people on the committee, all of whom decided that they were so busy that they couldn't devote the time to this that was really necessary.
So we went out and we got A.D.
to do the feasibility study, and that was a self-fulfilling prophecy.
They got $50,000 to find out it was a viable idea, and they said, yeah, this is a really viable idea.
And they came up with a master plan, and most of the plan was disregarded anyway.
But it was like, this now has been blessed.
At the same time, George decided, geez, while I'm doing this over here, I really ought to do something, and I'll just do this on the medical side.
So he went to A.D. Little again and said, take a look at the medical.
And his dream there was that something like Hark, but a collection of the medical research.
Do you see both of these things as having really emanated from George Mitchell per se?
Yeah.
Where was the input?
No, it was him.
It's him.
The whole superconductor, supercollider, again, never would have happened without Mitchell.
I mean, the guys at A&M, like Russ Houston and Peter McIntyre, no question about it.
played a very significant role.

But if George hadn't been there at the beginning and said, here's a facility, I'll put up money, here's housing for the scientists, I'll do this matching part, because I remember Russ Youth and I went to Chicago and signed that first contract with DOE, or the first magnet.
Oh, did you?
Okay.
And George had to make some serious commitments before.
There was nothing here.
Yeah, so...
Yeah, that's, those things I know.
I know that Hark and the medical, the research center, medically, never would have happened.
That's an interesting, it's almost a side issue that we have to, at some point, poke into, I guess, is that whole, because we got from Skip, what was it, chronology?
Yeah.
Of the development of the super...
Which is a story that hasn't been written yet.
Yeah.
Well, one of the first things that happened was, of course, the whole business of a site.
And the first money for that came from the governor's office.
And that was to look at various sites.
That was before the US Congress and the Department of Energy ever made the decision that we are going to go ahead and do a national search.
what the guys here were pushing for was, we've got, we're working on the magnets, let's go find a site in Texas.
And they got everybody, some of the people excited in the legislature, so they think at that time they came up with $400,000 to do a site study, six or seven sites.
I don't know, Skip, give you the...
I don't think we have to write it down, no, it's a search and sell.
But you're right, that is an interesting story.
And how...
and how the universities work together on it is also, it's another volume.
Yeah, I'm sure.
You know how tough it is getting departments to work together in a single university.
And what relevance did these in the park, for example, and the medical center have to the woodlands, do you think?
And you may have put yourself in Mitchell's mind, but what part of the package is this?
as an economic development type thing?
Yeah, yeah.
Is it for Woodlands growth or just... Yeah, I mean, George does a lot of things that are really quite altruistic, but there's always an intrinsic base.
I mean... As an economic historian...
He's very shrewd in the good things he does.
Yeah.
The idea is, for the Woodlands, is the name of the game here is job creation.
you create jobs here, then you're going to have all the other institutions, and you're going to sell homes.
And as that grows, it'll act as a magnet, attract other companies, etc.
And he recognized that.
And he also felt there was a real need.
He was very much taken by the North Carolina research tribe there.
That was a great thing to do.
His view was,
We've got great universities in Texas, is there any way to pull those together and have something analogous?
But yeah, with HARC, I think there George felt that having the HARC presence may act as some sort of magnet to bring in companies.
Because it was very clear that HARC was going to do contract research for the most part, and basic research, and hopefully there would be some spin-offs.
But HARC has pretty much remained... We're very, very sensitive about using HARC as a real estate initiative.
Right, yeah.
Skip made that very clear, too.
Are you still on the board?
No.
No.
No.
No, that's...
When I came to work for George, I went off that.
And it's better that way.
Yeah.
And I understand where Skip's coming from because in many respects he's trying to raise funds and people tend to see everything in the woodlands as George's playpen.
I think that's kind of overly overdone.
But however, so we really
is at arm's length.
We don't really get involved with that.
In the marketing materials we put together when we talk about the research for us, we'll have a picture of HARC and we'll talk about what they do.
But we're much more likely to utilize the medical, the biotech and biomed research labs and companies out here as a magnet for drawing than we are HARC.
And they're
they're far less sensitive to this.
In fact, Dominic Lamb is probably one of the best real estate people we got out here.
In fact, he overdoes it.
We interviewed him.
Dominic?
Yeah, well, make sure you got him on the front page, otherwise... That's right, I said that.
Our problem with Dominic very often is that he's got to make the point that there are other people out here other than Dominic.
He's so colorful, he's so hilarious that...
Now what is your major role in institutional development?
Just what do you do?
Well, that's a good question.
No.
I have primary responsibility for our relationships with the institutions and the medical center.
I play a major role in negotiating their moving their basic research.
Is there an advisory council now?
for that relationship at all?
We once had, at the beginning, kind of a woodlands research forest advisory group.
But that was at the very beginning.
But the thing has grown.
There are now 25 companies.
And I just recently put this together, in fact.
You might find that there's some.
We just put that together for a board, a Mitchell board.
The thing has grown to the point where at the beginning it was like a company town.

So we took responsibility for organizing and that, but it's grown to the point now that the CEOs of all of the companies in the Woodlands Research Force have their own organization and they meet about once a month.
And that's a very good reason because while some of them are mature
companies, a number of them are in the early stages of development.

So rather than each of them, you know, with six or seven or ten employees putting together their own health plans, insurance plans, that consortium they form allows them to do things on a group basis.
And they also get together just to share ideas.
The second thing that's emerged from that is a group called assets.
which is an association of the scientists and engineers and technicians out here.
And they meet four or five times a year on a fairly informal basis.
They'll have somebody come in as a lecturer, and they'll have beer together or lunch together.
And that is an organization that recently got started, and we're delighted about that.
And you had no role, basically, in starting those kind of arrangements?
We had the role of planting the seed, and I was very much involved in founding of the Forum Club of Houston, if you know about that.
Oh, it's something analogous to the Commonwealth Club in San Francisco.
It's now got about 3,700 members, and they're corporate people.
And they gather together 15 or 20 times a year, and major speakers are brought in.
Like today, the one I'm going to downtown today is O'Reilly, who is the head of EPA, and James Schlesinger is coming in January.
And they usually get anywhere from 800 to 1,200.
We really wanted to try to do something analogous to that out here with a focus on science and technology.
And now that group is reaching out to compact employees,
So we're trying to go beyond just here.
What was the seed that you planted for this asset group?
I mean, what exactly did you do?

Well, we had this advisory group, and then I went to a couple of the guys who were scientists, principal investigators, either in one of the university research labs or one of the companies, and said, you know, we now have over 200 PhD engineers and scientists out here, and many more technicians.
It would be a good idea to start getting these guys together in regular meetings.
We would find it helpful, for example, one of my jobs is to help facilitate the efforts of these people to reach their goals.
And I've done that in two ways.
I'm very active in connecting some of these startup companies with Japanese investors.
So we now have seven or eight different Japanese companies that have invested
either in some of the basic research going out here, or some of these startup companies.
Either R&D, equity, or handling marketing license.
Are you working with Sutter closely in that, or is it pretty independent?
No, it's pretty independent because... That's a different world.
Yeah, that was just a fluke.
Just three years ago I was invited to the Japanese government to spend a month in Japan.
touring and learning about MIDI and their companies and everything.
And that really got me started.
And so now I've been there five more times since then.
And we're doing a lot of joint venture.
We're initiating a lot of joint venture work with the Japanese and the Pacific Rim.
But if we can get capital into some of these startup companies and enhance their chances of survival, that's all for the best for us.
They stay alive and hire more people who buy more houses, who attract more attention.
And also, it draws attention to the Japanese.
So at this point, we have a Japanese pharmaceutical company that is probably going to be opening an office here.
It will be the first Japanese pharmaceutical company in the entire Southwest.
Our real estate people have just about signed.
They've already signed.
It's going to be finalized on the 19th.
a major real estate venture with a Japanese company on five buildings out here.
So that's one of the ways that we try, or through my role, try to enhance and facilitate their work.
The other is, a number of them will say, we need a library out here.
We need a library to be responsive to our proposal writing or whatever else we're doing.

We're not going to invest in a major university technical library here, but what we have said to them, get your group together, try to identify a set of generic journals or some electronic ways of retrieving library materials and we'll work with you.
Not that we're going to pay for it, we may fund part of it, we may help build a facility for it, but those are some of the ways that we need to group.
Another reason that
But that group is very, very helpful to us in helping us to identify other companies or other areas that we need to get involved in.
And the other nice thing about that group is they're terribly helpful when we're bringing in somebody who's considering potential payment.
And these are guys, by the way, that you can't give them a script.
You can't buy them.
Most of them are very, very helpful.
So the more of that sense of community that we build, the better it is.
They have an opportunity to interact with one another, and as a result of that, they discover new opportunities.
And I don't know if Skip told you about Bay Med.
No, I don't think he did.
Well, Russ Euston was over there working at his magnets.
Across the way here, Baylor College of Medicine has a magnetic resonance imaging center.
And they were doing theoretical work on imaging.
And so they had a need, and Russ had the technology and the concept, and they built this iron shield magnet together, formed a company called BayMed, and now are looking for investors.
And based on the stuff I've heard, they've got a pretty good chance of making it.
Surgimedics, which is a manufacturer...
Optic Fibers for Laser Research has connected with Mike Berry's Laser Application Research Center over there at Hark.

We've got a telecommunications company out here called Williams Telecommunications have now found a way of connecting with one of the biotech companies out here, Biomed companies that is involved in optics, fiber optics, a company called Optex.
So there's a lot of

You know how in a university you've got guys in physics working on one thing, guys in chemistry working on another, and if they knew what they each were working on, it would maximize their chances of success, even in getting funds.
Yeah, so here you're building vehicles on those bridges.
But again, they've made it very clear that they don't want that to be a Woodlands Corporation activity.
And we've made it equally clear, right, we don't want that either.

Well, you know, what I see here is something totally different to that new community thing that you read about in the Morgan King book, which I assume you've read and have sort of a take-off point in its oral history.
But this is a whole new world, a whole new ballgame that's developing out here in terms of this kind of relationship of business.
I think so.
I think that's why we... Porter, for example, I know, you know, he said, we're far beyond the wooden.
We're really thinking not just nationally, but internationally of what we try to do.
And they're doing a lot internationally, I think.
That's partly Skip, too, I know.
But by the same token, there is something there.
And with your Japanese...
In my view on that, I don't like it.
Okay.
But... Whatever thinking is going on over there,
It wouldn't be going on if it wasn't for George Mitchell.
I may admit it.
That's one thing that has come out of almost every candidate.
In fact, we have been in a lot of meetings like this with you.
And the photo ring with George Mitchell.
That's purely coincidental, but that gives you a sense of his involvement, acting involvement.
He's involved in the carpeting of the San Luis Hotel.
Yeah.
One of the things you gotta learn out here is when George calls you, what other six people has he called?
Yeah.
And given the same assignment.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
So your role then, in a way, seems a little amorphous.
Yeah.
It's the way you've described it.
I'm kind of like a cultural anthropologist.
One of my roles is I act as the interpreter and translator between the real estate people and the scientists.
I'm trying to benefit the people and the scientists.
My role also is once a company is here or a university, a company that has spun out of one of the universities, I work with them on a regular basis.
I visit with them.
How are things going?
What do you need?
What can we help you with?
What's the problem set?
And I get all kinds of phone calls.
Let me just give you an example.
Genesis, a company out here, wanted to recruit an Indian scientist from Princeton.
Really outstanding.
The other guy came out here, and how does he find housing?
So I linked him with our mortgage company.
His wife needs a job.
She's been teaching at some small college.
Can we help get her a job?
I connect her with a community college, and she gets a job.
All the way from...
Somebody from Houston Bio who's on the Governor's Science and Technology Committee calls and says the Governor's Committee wants to meet out here.
They have a limited budget.
Can we use the Woodlands Indian Country Club and get a box lunch?
That's facilitation as well.
Yeah, I mean, a lot of that.
We're now negotiating with MD Anderson for them to move a cancer research center out here.
There was some real serious misunderstandings between our real estate people.
who behave when they're selling real estate, it doesn't matter whether they're talking to a university or an electric company.
And there isn't that real understanding about academic research and the long terms and the need for publications and so forth.
And I got involved in that and acted as a facilitator on Boonsman and that's kind of what.
In addition to that,
George has me represent him on a number of educational projects that he gets involved in.
When he served on the Governor's Select Committee.
He gets an invitation from Corrigan, who's got this new educational enterprise at A&M, and they invite George to serve on it.
And he says, sure, and I go, you know he's now on your regents.
Yeah, Mitchell?
Yeah.
No, when did that happen?
I thought, somebody told me today.
This just happened then.
Yeah.
Because he wasn't.
Yeah, somebody told me.
I hope it's a reliable source.
Is that a new appointment by the new governor?
I don't know if it's by the new governor.
I mean, I don't know.
Somebody told me today.
You better, you check it out.
But anyway, he...
He's on the executive committee of the Greater Houston Partnership, which is this consortium of, you know, and the chamber there decided that a top priority was educational reform.
So they needed somebody to chair that study that they did.
So George volunteered, and they asked him, and he said, okay, he can do it.
One of the things that's...
surfaced repeatedly has been his effort to get a campus in the woodlands.
Do you know about that?
Oh, boy.
I mean, I would think that you would.
Yeah.
That's about a 20-year history.
And about 20 years ago, he and Cynthia Mitchell offered the University to use the 300 acres in the woodlands for the development of a four-year campus.
That's when Phil Hoffman was the president.
It was a three-year kind of gift.
You must have the state approval by three years, and if not, we'll renegotiate.
The closest that we came was when Mark White was governor.
And, oh, well.
Houston was supported, the university.
The university was supported.
Yeah, I mean, they kept taking the 300 acres.
How enthusiastic they were is difficult to determine.
Initially, what had happened is when the coordinating board approved the Clear Lake campus for the University of Houston,
They also said for the future that U of H would have a campus in the south, Clear Lake, and one in the north.
And people understood that to mean the woodlands.
And things were going along where that was still on the drawing board.
Then Phil Hoffman grabbed the University of Houston downtown as a campus.
And Ken Ashworth was really upset about that.
And Ashworth kind of took the position, well, there goes your campus in the north.
In any event, a proposal was made to the coordinating board to get preliminary funding, authorized preliminary funding, to do the design of a campus up here.
This was, I've got the whole chronology.
In fact, I'll loan you this.
I've already been curious about that.
This I prepared when I was at the University of Houston.
This was in 1982.
And here, well, it's... Or can we borrow it and photocopy it and send it back to you?
Sure, yeah.
The idea here was, the history's in here, et cetera.
But a presentation was made to the coordinating board
The day before the presentation was to be made, it was clear we had the votes.
When the presentation was being made, a couple of legislators came in representing the Huntsville area, where Huntsville is.
And Texas A&U?
Not Texas A&U.
I mean Sam Houston?
I mean Sam Houston at Huntsville.
were vehemently opposed to it by saying it would stifle the enrollments at Sam Houston, it would be competitive, it was a mistake, et cetera, et cetera.
So the Courting Board voted to defer that.
And Ashworth set certain conditions.
When the enrollment at Sam Houston reaches a certain level, when the population within 15 miles of here reaches a certain size,
and only if it's to be an upper-level college so it won't compete with freshman and sophomore.
Then we'll reconsider."

So four years later, they went back to the coordinating board and showed them that Sam Houston's enrollment had been lowered by the coordinating board itself, and even without any other competition out here, had never reached the goals.
The population, in fact, here had exceeded that 15-mile concentric zone.
And the idea was to have only a junior or senior anyway.
The Courting Board decided not to take any action.
A proposal was made in the Appropriations Committee of the Legislature to provide $250,000 to the University of Houston to begin planning a campus out here.
And everything was going along fine.
Then somebody, and it's the woman who headed up the Higher Education Committee,
What's her name, the black woman?
Yes.
She said that would jeopardize Prairie View,
And Mark White vetoed it.
Mark White vetoed it.
It was the only piece of the educational legislation that he vetoed.
So that's that aside.
Then after that... Well, I had heard once that A&M had been somewhat opposed to this, and that Bill Moore in particular.
No, what A&M had said on many occasions, and a lot of us tended to agree, was that if he would have given the land to A&M 20 years ago, there would be a campus here.
And many people agreed with that.
that if they had given it to A&M and given A&M's clout and their ability, there might have been something here.
In any event, the gift... Has that idea ever resurfaced?
Yeah.
Of A&M?
One of the things I'd like you to talk about a little bit is how central that idea is to Mr. Mitchell's vision for the Woodlands.
It's absolutely...
I would say if you were to ask him, if you had your one or two choices of what you would want here, what would it be, he would say a world-class university.
But a university, an advanced study center university, but at least starting with an upper-level university.
I would say that that would be a top priority to him.
And he's kicked around the idea of a private institution.
Some people suggested that.
Well, I was wondering about that, too.
Yeah, but we looked into that, and it was about $100 million.
And then we heard that some universities were thinking of relocating.
Trinity had come from somewhere else.
Well, that was a natural thing.
And so we heard about a few of those, and we went looking into that.
And it was best that those universities just close.
I did have discussions with people in A&M as recently as three years ago about trying to identify something at A&M that would be appropriate to have here.
In any event, then came the economic decline, and the legislature was talking about closing campus.
So finally, to bring it on up to where it is now,
They still have 300 acres.
If they don't do something, well, it's already too late to do something, it's getting something of legislative approval by 1990, which isn't going to happen, we're not even going to make a proposal.
About a year and a half ago,

Somebody from the University of Houston system said to me, if George Mitchell will do what the Cinco Ranch people did on the west side of Houston, I don't know if you know about that, they have a west Houston institute, the University of Houston.
Cinco Ranch gave them 10 acres of land free and put up a 40,000 square foot building.
Gave it to them.
If George Mitchell gives us 10 acres of land, puts up a two and a half million dollar building,

and locates it not in the woodland but someplace that's accessible we'd go for that and my reaction was you guys have more gall yeah because he already invested over five million dollars in the university and sure as hell he said okay and he offered him this 10 acres of land on i-45 and 242.
which made it accessible from north, south, east, west, and it's prime land.
It means right on 45.
And one, he's never even gotten a letter of acknowledgement.
And two, they're still debating whether it's the system that's supposed to act on it or the campus.
But I have now met the new president, Dr. Burnett, Marguerite Burnett.
She's going to do something.
I'm not sure what.
But I have the sense that she was going to do something with it.
I said to George a couple of years ago, do you have a problem if I start talking to people at A&M about it?
And his feeling was about wanting Houston out here had much more to do with the fact that someday he saw this as being annexed by Houston.
Yes, he's always said that.
And also that there would be a lot of U of H alumni in the area.
It wasn't, so he, that's what he wanted, but he wasn't adverse to somebody else coming in and making a plan.
And I did talk to people at A&M, this was about three years ago.
I don't know, I didn't get the sense that.
Of course there's all new players at the now.
I mean, I think, you know, Mowgli might, in fact, react quite differently.
It seems to me a very logical move, frankly.
I've always thought that they could do a basic division down here.
It wouldn't disturb anybody.
Just take the students who are going to be there anyway.
I had Kockenauer up here or down here with people from his international business program.
And I thought this could become an excellent center for studies and conferences and seminars in the whole international area, especially with a lot of biotech, biomed, technology opportunities.
So that's where that's at.
It's still up in the air.
Yeah.
But we're still working on it.
We now have submitted a proposal to the North Harris Community College, because they're probably going to have an election trying to incorporate Montgomery County as community college.
And we have a proposal to them offering, not as a gift,
we proposed 100 acres of land and some support as a possible site for their campus.
And it would be in that same place, I-45.
What's the thinking?
That's a different environment, community college, from what you're talking about earlier.
We're talking about two different animals.
That's right.
That's right.
What's the thinking behind that?
Well, because the community college they're talking about would be rather unique.
It would be somewhat of a nontraditional one with a very strong emphasis on science and technology.
advanced courses for seniors in high school.
And, in addition to that, I believe, and a lot of people tend to agree, that if we had a community college here doing freshman and sophomore, and the enrollments were constantly growing,
That's why I thought it was something like a basic division.
You can't even just teach basic divisions all over the country.
You wouldn't have to change enrollment.
